  // =============================================================================
  // GI HORMONES
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'gi-hormones',
    subjectId: 'physiology',
    subspecialtyId: 'physiology-gi',
    name: 'GI Hormones',
    slug: 'gi-hormones',
    description: 'Gastrin, secretin, CCK, GIP, motilin, somatostatin, ghrelin, GLP-1',
    content: {
      concept: `# GI Hormones

## Overview

GI hormones coordinate digestive processes by regulating **motility, secretion, and metabolism**. These peptide hormones are released from specialized enteroendocrine cells throughout the GI tract in response to nutrients and neural stimulation.

## Classification of GI Hormones

### True Hormones (Endocrine)
- Released into circulation
- Act on distant targets
- Examples: **Gastrin, Secretin, CCK, GIP**

### Paracrine Factors
- Act locally on nearby cells
- Examples: **Somatostatin, Histamine**

### Neurotransmitters/Neurocrines
- Released from nerve terminals
- Examples: **VIP, GRP (bombesin), Substance P**

### Candidate Hormones
- Physiological significance unclear
- Examples: **Motilin, Neurotensin, Enteroglucagon**

## Major GI Hormones

### Gastrin

#### Structure and Forms
- **G-17** (17 amino acids) - antral gastrin
- **G-34** (34 amino acids) - duodenal gastrin  
- **C-terminal tetrapeptide** (Trp-Met-Asp-Phe-NH2) contains all biological activity

#### Source and Stimuli
- **G cells** in gastric antrum and duodenum
- **Stimuli**: Protein, peptides, amino acids, gastric distention, vagal stimulation
- **Inhibited by**: Low pH (<3), somatostatin, secretin

#### Actions
| Target | Effect | Mechanism |
|--------|--------|-----------|
| **Parietal cells** | ↑ HCl secretion (indirect via ECL) | IP3/DAG |
| **ECL cells** | ↑ Histamine release | IP3/DAG |
| **Chief cells** | ↑ Pepsinogen secretion | IP3/DAG |
| **GI muscle** | ↑ Motility, ↑ LES tone | IP3/DAG |
| **Mucosa** | Trophic effect (growth) | Growth factor |

#### Clinical Significance
- **Zollinger-Ellison syndrome**: Gastrinoma → massive acid hypersecretion
- **H. pylori infection**: ↑ gastrin, ↓ somatostatin
- **PPI therapy**: Hypergastrinemia due to achlorhydria

### Secretin

#### Discovery and Structure  
- **First hormone discovered** (Bayliss & Starling, 1902)
- **27 amino acid peptide**
- **N-terminal region** essential for biological activity

#### Source and Stimuli
- **S cells** in duodenum and proximal jejunum
- **Primary stimulus**: Acid (pH <4.5) in duodenum
- **Secondary stimuli**: Fatty acids, bile acids

#### Actions
| Target | Effect | Mechanism |
|--------|--------|-----------|
| **Pancreatic ducts** | ↑ HCO3- secretion | cAMP/PKA |
| **Bile ducts** | ↑ HCO3- secretion | cAMP/PKA |
| **Gastric parietal cells** | ↓ HCl secretion | ↑ Somatostatin |
| **Pyloric sphincter** | ↓ Gastric emptying | Smooth muscle |

#### Clinical Applications
- **Secretin stimulation test**: Pancreatic function assessment
- **Zollinger-Ellison diagnosis**: Paradoxical gastrin rise

### Cholecystokinin (CCK)

#### Structure and Forms
- **CCK-8** (octapeptide) - most potent form
- **CCK-33** - predominant circulating form
- **C-terminal pentapeptide** contains biological activity
- **Shares C-terminal sequence** with gastrin

#### Source and Stimuli
- **I cells** in duodenum and jejunum  
- **Primary stimuli**: Fats, proteins, amino acids
- **Most potent triggers**: Long-chain fatty acids, aromatic amino acids

#### Actions
| Target | Effect | Mechanism |
|--------|--------|-----------|
| **Pancreatic acini** | ↑ Enzyme secretion | IP3/DAG/Ca2+ |
| **Gallbladder** | Contraction | IP3/DAG/Ca2+ |
| **Sphincter of Oddi** | Relaxation | NO/cGMP |
| **Gastric emptying** | Delayed | Smooth muscle |
| **Satiety center** | ↑ Satiety | Vagal afferents |

#### Clinical Significance
- **CCK deficiency**: Rare, causes pancreatic insufficiency
- **Diagnostic use**: HIDA scan (CCK-induced gallbladder contraction)

### Glucose-Dependent Insulinotropic Polypeptide (GIP)

#### Historical Names
- Originally **"Gastric Inhibitory Peptide"**
- Renamed when glucose-dependence discovered

#### Source and Stimuli
- **K cells** in duodenum and proximal jejunum
- **Stimuli**: Glucose, fats, amino acids (oral route)
- **Glucose-dependent** - only active when blood glucose is elevated

#### Actions
| Target | Effect | Mechanism |
|--------|--------|-----------|
| **Pancreatic β-cells** | ↑ Insulin release (glucose-dependent) | cAMP/PKA |
| **Gastric acid** | ↓ HCl secretion | Indirect |
| **Gastric emptying** | Delayed | Smooth muscle |

#### Clinical Significance
- **Incretin effect**: Explains why oral glucose causes greater insulin response than IV glucose
- **Type 2 diabetes**: GIP resistance contributes to pathophysiology
- **GLP-1 agonists**: Therapeutic agents based on incretin physiology

### Glucagon-Like Peptide-1 (GLP-1)

#### Structure and Processing
- Derived from **proglucagon** (same gene as glucagon)
- **Tissue-specific processing**: 
  - Pancreas → glucagon
  - Intestine → GLP-1, GLP-2

#### Source and Stimuli
- **L cells** in distal ileum and colon
- **Stimuli**: Nutrients (especially glucose), neural stimulation
- **Rapid degradation** by DPP-4 enzyme

#### Actions
| Target | Effect | Mechanism |
|--------|--------|-----------|
| **Pancreatic β-cells** | ↑ Insulin (glucose-dependent) | cAMP/PKA |
| **Pancreatic α-cells** | ↓ Glucagon | cAMP inhibition |
| **Gastric emptying** | Markedly delayed | Smooth muscle |
| **Brain** | ↑ Satiety, ↓ food intake | Hypothalamus |
| **β-cell mass** | Proliferation, ↓ apoptosis | Growth factors |

#### Therapeutic Applications
- **GLP-1 agonists**: Exenatide, liraglutide, dulaglutide
- **DPP-4 inhibitors**: Sitagliptin, saxagliptin
- **Weight loss**: Semaglutide approved for obesity

### Motilin

#### Source and Stimuli
- **Mo cells** in duodenum and jejunum
- **Released during fasting** (interdigestive period)
- **Cyclical release** every 90-120 minutes

#### Actions
- **Initiates MMC** (migrating motor complex)
- **"Housekeeper waves"** - clears undigested material
- **Coordinates interdigestive motility**

#### Clinical Significance
- **Motilin agonists**: Erythromycin (prokinetic effect)
- **Gastroparesis**: Altered motilin rhythm

### Somatostatin

#### Source and Forms
- **D cells** throughout GI tract
- **SS-14** (14 amino acids) - predominant form
- **SS-28** (28 amino acids) - longer half-life

#### Stimuli
- **Low gastric pH** (<3)
- **High blood glucose**
- **Various hormones and nutrients**

#### Actions - **"Universal Inhibitor"**
| Target | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| **Gastrin** | ↓ Release from G cells |
| **HCl** | ↓ Secretion from parietal cells |
| **Insulin/Glucagon** | ↓ Release from islet cells |
| **GI motility** | ↓ Smooth muscle contraction |
| **Splanchnic blood flow** | ↓ Vasoconstriction |

#### Clinical Applications
- **Octreotide**: Synthetic analog
- **Uses**: Acromegaly, carcinoid syndrome, variceal bleeding
- **VIPomas**: Watery diarrhea syndrome

### Ghrelin

#### Discovery and Structure
- **"Hunger hormone"** discovered in 1999
- **28 amino acid peptide**
- **Unique acyl modification** required for activity

#### Source and Stimuli
- **P/D1 cells** in gastric fundus
- **Released during fasting** - rises before meals
- **Suppressed by feeding**

#### Actions
| Target | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| **Hypothalamus** | ↑ Hunger, ↑ food intake |
| **Pituitary** | ↑ Growth hormone release |
| **Gastric motility** | ↑ Emptying |

#### Clinical Significance
- **Obesity**: Altered ghrelin patterns
- **Post-bariatric surgery**: Reduced ghrelin may contribute to weight loss

## Hormone Interactions and Integration

### Cephalic Phase
- **Neural stimulation** → gastrin release
- **Prepares GI tract** for incoming food

### Gastric Phase  
- **Gastrin** dominates
- **Positive feedback** until pH drops

### Intestinal Phase
- **Secretin** (acid neutralization)
- **CCK** (enzyme secretion, gallbladder contraction)
- **GIP/GLP-1** (insulin response)

### Fed vs Fasted State
- **Fed**: Gastrin, secretin, CCK, GIP, GLP-1 active
- **Fasted**: Motilin, ghrelin active

## Clinical Applications

### Diagnostic Tests
- **Gastrin**: ZES, H. pylori effects
- **Secretin stimulation**: Pancreatic function
- **CCK**: Gallbladder function

### Therapeutic Targets
- **PPIs**: Block gastrin's target (H+-K+-ATPase)
- **Incretin-based therapy**: GLP-1 agonists, DPP-4 inhibitors
- **Somatostatin analogs**: Octreotide for neuroendocrine tumors

> 💎 **High Yield**: Secretin was the first hormone discovered and stimulates bicarbonate secretion. CCK stimulates enzyme secretion and gallbladder contraction. GLP-1 and GIP are incretins that enhance glucose-dependent insulin release. Somatostatin is the universal GI inhibitor.`,
