    content: {
      concept: `# Carbohydrate Digestion & Absorption

## Overview

Carbohydrates provide **45-65% of dietary calories** and are the body's preferred energy source. Complex carbohydrates must be digested to **monosaccharides** (glucose, fructose, galactose) before absorption. This process involves multiple enzymes and transport systems.

## Dietary Carbohydrates

### Classification by Complexity
| Type | Examples | Digestibility |
|------|----------|---------------|
| **Monosaccharides** | Glucose, fructose, galactose | Ready for absorption |
| **Disaccharides** | Sucrose, lactose, maltose | Require brush border enzymes |
| **Oligosaccharides** | Raffinose, stachyose | Partially digestible |
| **Polysaccharides** | Starch, glycogen | Require amylase |
| **Fiber** | Cellulose, pectin | Indigestible by human enzymes |

### Major Dietary Sources
- **Starch** (60-70%): Grains, potatoes, legumes
- **Sucrose** (20-30%): Table sugar, fruits
- **Lactose** (5-10%): Dairy products
- **Fiber**: Vegetables, fruits, whole grains

## Starch Digestion

### Starch Structure
- **Amylose** (20-30%): Linear α-1,4 glucose chains
- **Amylopectin** (70-80%): Branched chains with α-1,6 bonds every 20-30 glucose units
- **Resistant starch**: Physically protected or retrograded starch

### Salivary α-Amylase
#### Properties
- **Secretion**: 1-1.5 L saliva/day containing amylase
- **pH optimum**: 6.7 (close to salivary pH)
- **Substrate**: Internal α-1,4 bonds (endoglucosidase)
- **Products**: Maltotriose, maltose, α-limit dextrins

#### Limitations
- **Short contact time** in mouth
- **Inactivated by gastric acid** (pH <4)
- **Limited digestion** (~5% of starch)

### Pancreatic α-Amylase
#### Properties
- **Major starch-digesting enzyme**
- **Identical to salivary amylase** but different source
- **pH optimum**: 7-8 (pancreatic juice pH)
- **Requires Cl⁻ and Ca²⁺** for optimal activity

#### Mechanism
\`\`\`
Starch Structure:
Glucose-α1,4-Glucose-α1,4-Glucose-α1,6-Glucose...

Amylase Action:
• Cleaves internal α-1,4 bonds randomly
• Cannot cleave α-1,6 bonds (branch points)
• Cannot cleave terminal bonds

Products:
• Maltotriose (3 glucose units)
• Maltose (2 glucose units)  
• α-limit dextrins (branched oligosaccharides)
\`\`\`

#### Clinical Significance
- **Serum amylase**: Elevated in pancreatitis (but also parotitis, bowel obstruction)
- **Not essential**: Brush border enzymes can compensate if amylase deficient

## Brush Border Digestion

### Brush Border Enzyme Complex
Located on **microvilli of small intestinal enterocytes**:

#### Oligosaccharidases
| Enzyme | Substrate | Products |
|---------|-----------|----------|
| **Maltase** | Maltose, maltotriose | Glucose |
| **Isomaltase** | α-limit dextrins, isomaltose | Glucose |
| **Sucrase** | Sucrose | Glucose + Fructose |
| **Lactase** | Lactose | Glucose + Galactose |

#### Key Features
- **Membrane-bound enzymes** on apical surface
- **High local concentration** creates efficient digestion
- **Coupled to transport** - products immediately available for absorption
- **Developmental regulation** - especially lactase

### Lactase Physiology
#### Normal Development
- **High in infancy** - essential for milk digestion
- **Physiologic decline** after weaning in most mammals
- **Persistence in some humans** - genetic adaptation

#### Lactase Persistence
- **Genetic polymorphism** - dominant trait
- **Geographic distribution**: 
  - High: Northern Europeans (95%), some Africans/Middle Eastern
  - Low: East Asians (5-10%), many Africans

#### Lactose Intolerance
- **Primary**: Genetically programmed lactase decline
- **Secondary**: Disease-induced (gastroenteritis, celiac disease)
- **Symptoms**: Bloating, diarrhea, gas after dairy consumption
- **Mechanism**: Undigested lactose → osmotic diarrhea + bacterial fermentation

## Monosaccharide Absorption

### Transport Mechanisms Overview
\`\`\`
Apical Membrane (Lumen → Cell):
• SGLT1: Na⁺-glucose/galactose cotransporter
• GLUT5: Fructose transporter (facilitated diffusion)

Basolateral Membrane (Cell → Blood):
• GLUT2: Glucose, fructose, galactose transporter
\`\`\`

### SGLT1 (Sodium-Glucose Cotransporter 1)
#### Structure and Function
- **2:1 stoichiometry**: 2 Na⁺ : 1 glucose
- **Active transport** driven by Na⁺ gradient (maintained by Na⁺-K⁺-ATPase)
- **High affinity, low capacity**
- **Km for glucose**: ~0.3 mM

#### Substrate Specificity
- **Glucose and galactose**: High affinity
- **Fructose**: Not transported by SGLT1
- **Requires D-configuration** and specific stereochemistry

#### Regulation
- **Dietary adaptation**: High carbohydrate diet ↑ SGLT1 expression
- **Hormonal**: Insulin ↑, cortisol ↑ SGLT1
- **Pathological**: Diabetes ↑ intestinal SGLT1

### GLUT5 (Fructose Transporter)
#### Properties
- **Facilitated diffusion** (no energy requirement)
- **Fructose-specific** - does not transport glucose
- **High Km**: Lower affinity than SGLT1 for glucose
- **Rate-limiting step** for fructose absorption

#### Distribution
- **Highest in jejunum** - decreases distally
- **Upregulated by dietary fructose**
- **Also present in muscle, adipose tissue**

#### Clinical Significance
- **Fructose malabsorption**: GLUT5 dysfunction or saturation
- **High fructose intake**: Can overwhelm transport capacity
- **Symptoms**: Similar to lactose intolerance

### GLUT2 (Basolateral Glucose Transporter)
#### Properties
- **High Km, high capacity** - allows rapid equilibration
- **Transports glucose, fructose, galactose**
- **Insulin-independent** (unlike muscle GLUT4)
- **Bidirectional** transport

#### Function
- **Exit pathway** for absorbed monosaccharides
- **Maintains concentration gradient** for continued absorption
- **Portal circulation** → liver first-pass metabolism

## Integration of Digestion and Absorption

### Sequential Process
\`\`\`
Mouth: Salivary amylase (limited)
      ↓
Stomach: Acid inactivation
      ↓  
Duodenum: Pancreatic amylase (major digestion)
      ↓
Jejunum: Brush border enzymes + absorption (90%)
      ↓
Ileum: Remaining absorption (10%)
\`\`\`

### Capacity and Efficiency
- **Normal capacity**: >500g glucose/day
- **Efficiency**: >95% absorption of digestible carbohydrates
- **Reserve capacity**: Can increase 3-5 fold with adaptation

### Factors Affecting Absorption
#### Enhancing Factors
- **Sodium availability** - drives SGLT1
- **Adequate brush border enzyme activity**
- **Normal intestinal transit time**

#### Inhibiting Factors
- **Rapid transit** (diarrhea, dumping syndrome)
- **Brush border enzyme deficiency**
- **Intestinal disease** (celiac, Crohn's)
- **Competitive inhibition** (phlorizin blocks SGLT1)

## Clinical Applications

### Malabsorption Syndromes
#### Causes
- **Enzyme deficiencies**: Lactase, sucrase-isomaltase
- **Transport defects**: Glucose-galactose malabsorption (SGLT1 deficiency)
- **Intestinal disease**: Celiac disease, tropical sprue, short bowel syndrome

#### Clinical Features
- **Osmotic diarrhea**: Unabsorbed carbohydrates
- **Bacterial fermentation**: Gas, bloating, acidic stools
- **Nutritional deficiency**: Carbohydrate malnutrition

### Glucose-Galactose Malabsorption
- **Rare genetic disorder** - SGLT1 mutations
- **Severe diarrhea** from birth with glucose/galactose feeding
- **Fructose tolerance** - normal GLUT5 function
- **Treatment**: Fructose-based diet

### Sucrase-Isomaltase Deficiency
- **Most common disaccharidase deficiency** (after lactase)
- **Higher prevalence** in Inuit populations
- **Symptoms**: Sucrose and starch intolerance
- **Treatment**: Low sucrose diet, enzyme supplementation

### Therapeutic Applications
#### Oral Rehydration Therapy (ORT)
- **Principle**: SGLT1-mediated Na⁺ and water absorption
- **Composition**: Glucose + Na⁺ + Cl⁻ + K⁺
- **Effectiveness**: Treats dehydration even during secretory diarrhea

#### Diabetes Management
- **α-glucosidase inhibitors**: Acarbose, miglitol
- **Mechanism**: Inhibit brush border enzymes
- **Effect**: Delayed carbohydrate absorption, reduced postprandial glucose

### Diagnostic Tests
#### Lactose Tolerance Test
- **Procedure**: Oral lactose load, measure blood glucose rise
- **Normal**: Glucose rise >20 mg/dL
- **Lactose intolerance**: Minimal glucose rise

#### Hydrogen Breath Test
- **Principle**: Unabsorbed carbohydrates → bacterial fermentation → H₂ production
- **Uses**: Lactose intolerance, small bowel overgrowth, transit time

> 💎 **High Yield**: SGLT1 cotransports 2 Na⁺ with 1 glucose/galactose using the Na⁺ gradient. GLUT5 transports fructose by facilitated diffusion. Lactase persistence is a genetic adaptation allowing adult milk consumption. ORT works because SGLT1 continues to function during secretory diarrhea.`,
      keyPoints: [
